---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import vocabularies from "../../data/generated/vocabularies.json";
---
<BaseLayout title="About & Method - Awesome Autonomous Biology" current="about">
  <div class="shell">
    <header class="page-head"><div><p class="eyebrow">METHOD - AUDITABLE BY DESIGN</p><h1>A map with<br />hard epistemic edges.</h1><p class="lede">The atlas stays useful by separating identity, loop function, evidence, autonomy, and curation state.</p></div><span class="signal">Human-gated verified data</span></header>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Inclusion boundary</h2><p>A resource must be biology-specific and directly support one or more stages of a closed biological discovery loop. Generic AI, robotics, or laboratory automation is excluded unless the biology connection is direct and evidenced.</p><div class="callout"><strong>Automation != scientific autonomy. Inclusion != endorsement.</strong> Remote execution, AI use, or robot control alone does not establish end-to-end scientific autonomy.</div>
      <h2>Five resource classes</h2><dl class="definition-list"><dt>core_autonomous_system</dt><dd>An integrated system that closes substantive scientific and operational loop segments.</dd><dt>scientific_decision_module</dt><dd>A model or agent involved in hypothesis, selection, interpretation, feedback, or next-experiment decisions.</dd><dt>enabling_infrastructure</dt><dd>Protocols, orchestration, instruments, hardware, standards, or services that enable loop execution.</dd><dt>data_evaluation_resource</dt><dd>Datasets, simulators, benchmarks, or evaluation resources.</dd><dt>ecosystem_education</dt><dd>Perspectives, tutorials, communities, and field-level entry points.</dd></dl>
      <h2>Evidence grades</h2><dl class="definition-list">{Object.entries(vocabularies.evidence_grades).map(([grade, definition]) => <><dt>Grade {grade}</dt><dd>{definition}</dd></>)}</dl>
      <h2>Two autonomy axes</h2><p><strong>Scientific autonomy</strong> concerns participation in biological questions, hypotheses, experiment selection, interpretation, model updating, or next-round decisions. <strong>Operational autonomy</strong> concerns protocol execution, equipment control, measurement, and laboratory orchestration. The controlled levels are: {vocabularies.autonomy_levels.join(", ")}.</p>
      <h2>Review workflow</h2><ol class="steps"><li>Deterministic public APIs and RSS feeds discover candidates.</li><li>Normalization standardizes DOI, URL, title, authors, date, and source type.</li><li>DOI -> canonical URL -> normalized title deduplication runs.</li><li>A transparent candidate score prioritizes human attention.</li><li>Candidates enter GitHub issues as review_pending only.</li><li>A curator verifies identity, primary sources, scope, autonomy, links, and license warnings.</li><li>A reviewed PR may add a verified record with last_verified, curator, and decision_note.</li><li>Schema, controlled vocabulary, relation, README-sync, test, and build checks run.</li><li>Pages redeploys the human-approved Atlas.</li></ol>
      <h2>Data fields</h2><p>The strict schema covers identity, category, resource class/types, biology domains, nine loop stages, wet-lab involvement, separate autonomy levels, openness/license notes, canonical and typed URLs, evidence, bilingual summaries, boundary notes, explicit relations, and curation audit metadata.</p>
      <h2>Phase 2 agent interface</h2><p>A future optional assistant may propose summaries, categories, or duplicate judgments. Its output must remain <code>review_pending</code>, preserve provenance, work as an optional layer, and never write verified YAML directly. v0.1 requires no model key.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
